{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17613543","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17613543"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T14:36:34+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T14:36:34+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16316"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16316","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16316"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.27,0.09,0.05,0.59,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9007"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116117"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9007","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9007"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16316"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98113"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1992"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4946"},{"type":"tags","id":"5586"},{"type":"tags","id":"7519"},{"type":"tags","id":"7527"},{"type":"tags","id":"7531"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21435"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21439"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22747"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116117","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/116117"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe retina contains specialised regions with varying densities of photoreceptor cells that are crucial for different aspects of vision.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following structures contains the highest density of photoreceptors?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Optic disc","Peripheral retina","Ora serrata","Macula lutea","Ciliary body"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Emacula lutea\u003C/strong\u003E (or fovea) is a specialised region in the central retina that contains the highest density of cone photoreceptors. At its center is the fovea centralis, which is responsible for high-acuity central vision and color perception.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eoptic disc\u003C/strong\u003E is the exit point of the optic nerve and contains no photoreceptors (blind spot). The \u003Cstrong\u003Eperipheral retina\u003C/strong\u003E has a lower density of photoreceptors, mainly rods. The \u003Cstrong\u003Eora serrata\u003C/strong\u003E is the anterior border of the retina where it meets the ciliary body. The \u003Cstrong\u003Eciliary body\u003C/strong\u003E is part of the uveal tract and contains no photoreceptors.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe macula lutea appears yellow due to the presence of xanthophyll pigments, which help protect the retina from harmful blue light.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The macula lutea is the central region of the retina containing the highest density of cone photoreceptors.","The fovea centralis, located at the center of the macula, has the highest concentration of cones and is responsible for sharp central vision."],"references":["Probst, L., \u0026 Tsai, J. (2024). Ophthalmology: Clinical and Surgical Principles. CRC Press.","Salmon, J. F. (2024). Kanski\u0027s Clinical Ophthalmology E-Book: A Systematic Approach. Elsevier Health Sciences.","Kels BD, Grzybowski A, Grant-Kels JM. Human ocular anatomy. Clin Dermatol. 2015 Mar-Apr;33(2):140-6. doi: 10.1016/j.clindermatol.2014.10.006. PMID: 25704934."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98113"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16316"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data